1
00:00:07,862 --> 00:00:10,698
Abrasions on the hand…

2
00:00:10,782 --> 00:00:13,743
…rib fracture… from CPR…

3
00:00:14,577 --> 00:00:16,204
Darn! This will never end.

4
00:00:16,287 --> 00:00:17,372
You scared me.

5
00:00:17,455 --> 00:00:19,541
Too many reports. Someone take over.

6
00:00:19,624 --> 00:00:21,084
I'm busy organizing files.

7
00:00:21,167 --> 00:00:22,627
Same, I got inspection reports.

8
00:00:22,710 --> 00:00:23,670
I can't either.

9
00:00:26,923 --> 00:00:29,759
The MEJ is different from what I imagined.

10
00:00:29,843 --> 00:00:30,844
Tell me about it.

11
00:00:30,927 --> 00:00:34,222
Makes me want to go back
to university research labs ASAP.

12
00:00:35,181 --> 00:00:36,474
Dr. Honda, you're finished?

13
00:00:36,558 --> 00:00:38,810
-With ease.
-I still have some, if you're free.

14
00:00:38,893 --> 00:00:39,978
I have plans tonight.

15
00:00:40,061 --> 00:00:41,104
Oh, a date.

16
00:00:41,187 --> 00:00:42,105
No.

17
00:00:42,188 --> 00:00:44,232
Going for drinks with an old colleague.

18
00:00:44,315 --> 00:00:45,358
Lucky.

19
00:00:45,441 --> 00:00:46,818
See you later.

20
00:00:49,487 --> 00:00:51,739
Shall we get to it then?

21
00:00:53,241 --> 00:00:54,117
Okay.

22
00:00:55,994 --> 00:01:00,123
…the coronary artery tissue of…

23
00:01:01,166 --> 00:01:02,792
Dr. Matsubara.

24
00:01:03,293 --> 00:01:05,295
-Can you put yourself on mute?
-What?

25
00:01:06,713 --> 00:01:07,964
Sorry.

26
00:01:09,757 --> 00:01:10,717
Welcome.

27
00:01:10,800 --> 00:01:11,676
Hello.

28
00:01:14,762 --> 00:01:15,763
Hey!

29
00:01:16,222 --> 00:01:17,473
Hirono.

30
00:01:17,557 --> 00:01:18,808
Here's your <i>oden.</i>

31
00:01:18,892 --> 00:01:20,602
Hey, do you remember?

32
00:01:21,144 --> 00:01:23,521
That massive pile-up on the highway.

33
00:01:23,605 --> 00:01:25,523
Of course, I remember.

34
00:01:25,607 --> 00:01:27,692
That was brutal.

35
00:01:27,775 --> 00:01:29,694
We saw 30 patients in one night.

36
00:01:29,777 --> 00:01:31,487
Pretty much just the two of us.

37
00:01:31,571 --> 00:01:34,657
Once you've survived a scene like that,
nothing scares you anymore.

38
00:01:34,741 --> 00:01:35,742
True.

39
00:01:35,825 --> 00:01:39,537
And then, we had a toast
in that empty lobby afterward.

40
00:01:39,621 --> 00:01:42,957
That canned beer
was the best in the world at that moment.

41
00:01:43,541 --> 00:01:46,002
Spoken like a guy
who was drinking non-alcoholic.

42
00:01:47,795 --> 00:01:50,798
More importantly, how's the new workplace?

43
00:01:51,382 --> 00:01:52,675
MEJ, is it?

44
00:01:53,927 --> 00:01:54,844
Yes.

45
00:01:55,637 --> 00:01:56,638
It's the worst.

46
00:01:56,721 --> 00:01:57,805
Really?

47
00:01:57,889 --> 00:02:00,391
The police and everyone else
find us annoying.

48
00:02:00,975 --> 00:02:03,144
<i>I have no idea what my boss is thinking.</i>

49
00:02:03,228 --> 00:02:04,771
<i>He's a weirdo.</i>

50
00:02:05,355 --> 00:02:07,649
I'm worked to the bone for low pay, too.

51
00:02:07,732 --> 00:02:08,650
I see.

52
00:02:09,317 --> 00:02:10,902
You've got it good.

53
00:02:10,985 --> 00:02:13,696
Settled in nicely as a surgeon
at Meiwa University.

54
00:02:14,280 --> 00:02:16,699
I should never have gone
into forensic medicine.

55
00:02:20,745 --> 00:02:22,121
Honda, you know--

56
00:02:22,205 --> 00:02:25,208
Don't start with the comforting words.

57
00:02:39,889 --> 00:02:42,350
-Sorry, it's work.
-Top doctors have it tough.

58
00:02:42,433 --> 00:02:44,686
Sorry, it's work I really can't miss.

59
00:02:44,769 --> 00:02:45,603
Sure.

60
00:02:46,062 --> 00:02:47,814
I'll make it up to you next time.

61
00:02:51,025 --> 00:02:51,943
You know, I--

62
00:02:52,026 --> 00:02:53,236
Just go.

63
00:02:53,319 --> 00:02:54,278
You're busy, right?

64
00:02:57,281 --> 00:02:59,117
Let's talk properly next time.

65
00:03:00,702 --> 00:03:02,286
Good luck.

66
00:03:09,711 --> 00:03:11,921
My head hurts.

67
00:03:12,005 --> 00:03:13,214
A hangover?

68
00:03:13,297 --> 00:03:15,133
Coming into work after partying?

69
00:03:15,216 --> 00:03:16,551
That's just wrong.

70
00:03:16,634 --> 00:03:17,719
You stink.

71
00:03:17,802 --> 00:03:20,638
I went home after
my friend got called into work.

72
00:03:20,722 --> 00:03:22,432
-An emergency patient?
-Yes.

73
00:03:22,515 --> 00:03:24,642
He's a surgeon at Meiwa University.

74
00:03:24,726 --> 00:03:27,103
He's moving up in the world. Unlike you.

75
00:03:27,186 --> 00:03:30,523
Dr. Honda, the toxicology report…

76
00:03:30,606 --> 00:03:32,191
I turned it in yesterday.

77
00:03:32,275 --> 00:03:35,820
There's an error in the diagnosis
of the poison, please fix it.

78
00:03:35,903 --> 00:03:38,906
No way, I was certain
everything was correct.

79
00:03:38,990 --> 00:03:42,702
No, the lethal dose of Olanzapine
was overlooked.

80
00:03:43,411 --> 00:03:44,370
Oh.

81
00:03:46,748 --> 00:03:48,333
This is Medical Examiner Japan.

82
00:03:48,416 --> 00:03:51,586
Someone please also
cross-reference it with past cases?

83
00:03:52,462 --> 00:03:53,629
Okay.

84
00:03:53,713 --> 00:03:56,382
There's so much to do
even without any autopsies.

85
00:03:56,466 --> 00:03:58,092
I wish we got paid extra.

86
00:03:59,886 --> 00:04:01,095
Yes.

87
00:04:03,139 --> 00:04:05,224
Yes, goodbye.

88
00:04:09,437 --> 00:04:10,605
Dr. Honda.

89
00:04:10,688 --> 00:04:11,773
Yeah?

90
00:04:12,607 --> 00:04:14,067
Where did your friend work?

91
00:04:14,692 --> 00:04:16,027
Meiwa University Hospital?

92
00:04:16,110 --> 00:04:17,487
What was that call?

93
00:04:18,821 --> 00:04:21,616
There's a body of a person
who died an unnatural death.

94
00:04:23,493 --> 00:04:24,452
What?

95
00:04:39,008 --> 00:04:40,385
This can't be real.

96
00:04:41,803 --> 00:04:43,388
He knows the victim?

97
00:04:44,263 --> 00:04:45,723
It seems he was his friend.

98
00:04:45,807 --> 00:04:47,975
They went drinking together last night.

99
00:04:48,059 --> 00:04:51,229
Ms. Dojima! We haven't been able
to find his smartphone.

100
00:04:51,312 --> 00:04:53,189
There are no surveillance cameras nearby.

101
00:04:53,272 --> 00:04:55,066
We don't know what happened.

102
00:04:57,527 --> 00:04:58,569
The cause of death

103
00:04:58,653 --> 00:05:01,114
was a cerebral contusion
from a strong blow to the head.

104
00:05:01,197 --> 00:05:05,660
Or perhaps internal organ damage
from multiple fractures.

105
00:05:05,743 --> 00:05:09,038
This is a condition seen
when there is a violent collision.

106
00:05:09,122 --> 00:05:10,540
Like a traffic accident?

107
00:05:10,623 --> 00:05:13,251
In that case,
there would usually be secondary injuries

108
00:05:13,334 --> 00:05:16,337
from being thrown onto the hood
or windshield,

109
00:05:16,421 --> 00:05:19,757
and tertiary ones
from hitting the road's surface.

110
00:05:20,383 --> 00:05:21,259
It doesn't add up.

111
00:05:21,342 --> 00:05:22,427
It doesn't add up.

112
00:05:22,510 --> 00:05:23,469
It doesn't add up.

113
00:05:23,553 --> 00:05:24,720
Rather than that,

114
00:05:25,304 --> 00:05:29,517
it looks as though he fell
from several meters above.

115
00:05:34,105 --> 00:05:36,315
Are you saying he fell from the sky?

116
00:05:36,399 --> 00:05:38,860
An example, going by the evidence I see.

117
00:05:38,943 --> 00:05:41,237
-Supervisor.
-Yes?

118
00:05:41,946 --> 00:05:45,533
Maybe the crime scene was elsewhere,
and he was moved here? Or something?

119
00:05:45,616 --> 00:05:48,578
There are blood droplets
directly beneath the body.

120
00:05:48,661 --> 00:05:50,079
It doesn't add up.

121
00:05:50,163 --> 00:05:51,455
In any case,

122
00:05:51,539 --> 00:05:54,959
he must have fallen somewhere
not too far from here.

123
00:05:55,042 --> 00:05:58,337
Well, even if you say it's not too far…

124
00:05:59,088 --> 00:06:00,923
-He really fell from the sky?
-Idiot!

125
00:06:01,007 --> 00:06:04,343
Don't say stupid stuff, it's annoying.

126
00:06:04,427 --> 00:06:05,428
Sorry.

127
00:06:05,511 --> 00:06:07,263
These bloodstains…

128
00:06:10,183 --> 00:06:11,559
What is it?

129
00:06:12,393 --> 00:06:14,896
Possibly from when he fell,

130
00:06:14,979 --> 00:06:19,150
but in that case
the amount of blood is far too small.

131
00:06:24,155 --> 00:06:25,656
It doesn't add up.

132
00:06:27,116 --> 00:06:29,202
Could we ask you a few questions?

133
00:06:31,495 --> 00:06:32,747
Sure.

134
00:06:32,830 --> 00:06:35,750
Okay. First, what was your relationship
with the victim?

135
00:06:37,043 --> 00:06:40,421
We were colleagues when we worked
as ER doctors.

136
00:06:41,839 --> 00:06:43,841
And you were with him last night?

137
00:06:43,925 --> 00:06:45,343
We had dinner.

138
00:06:45,426 --> 00:06:46,844
What time?

139
00:06:47,553 --> 00:06:48,804
Dr. Honda.

140
00:06:50,514 --> 00:06:53,059
You don't have to do the autopsy.
You can take--

141
00:06:53,142 --> 00:06:54,227
Bureaucrats

142
00:06:55,186 --> 00:06:56,562
are soft, aren't they?

143
00:07:38,479 --> 00:07:39,772
Let's begin.

144
00:08:00,960 --> 00:08:04,922
As a result of the autopsy,
the direct cause of death was indeed

145
00:08:05,006 --> 00:08:08,092
a cerebral contusion from a strong
impact to the back of the head.

146
00:08:08,175 --> 00:08:09,427
However, before that,

147
00:08:09,510 --> 00:08:11,721
Mr. Hirono took a heavy blow
to his lower back.

148
00:08:11,804 --> 00:08:14,765
<i>I believe there is no doubt</i>
<i>that he fell from a height</i>

149
00:08:14,849 --> 00:08:17,893
<i>of about ten meters, landing on his back.</i>

150
00:08:19,145 --> 00:08:22,815
At the moment, we have no reports
of people falling out of airplanes.

151
00:08:22,898 --> 00:08:23,816
Of course not.

152
00:08:23,899 --> 00:08:27,612
Furthermore, there were abrasions
on his right arm and left leg,

153
00:08:27,695 --> 00:08:30,281
as if something had rubbed
against the skin.

154
00:08:30,364 --> 00:08:31,699
They look like burns.

155
00:08:31,782 --> 00:08:34,619
I wonder. Doesn't look like
the skin is peeling either.

156
00:08:34,702 --> 00:08:36,621
What do you mean, they look like burns?

157
00:08:37,246 --> 00:08:38,831
So he did not actually fall?

158
00:08:38,914 --> 00:08:42,960
These injuries were not fatal,
and no doubt it was a death from falling.

159
00:08:46,130 --> 00:08:48,424
Something bothering me is

160
00:08:49,884 --> 00:08:52,011
that there is absolutely
no gas in his intestines.

161
00:08:52,094 --> 00:08:54,096
His rectus abdominis muscle
is expanded out.

162
00:08:54,180 --> 00:08:56,641
Temporary post-mortem expansion?

163
00:08:57,433 --> 00:08:58,351
Probably.

164
00:08:58,434 --> 00:08:59,852
Expansion?

165
00:08:59,935 --> 00:09:01,812
Is there a connection to the fall?

166
00:09:01,896 --> 00:09:03,689
That is also unknown.

167
00:09:03,773 --> 00:09:04,732
Also,

168
00:09:04,815 --> 00:09:08,027
in the back of his throat,
his lungs, and his hair

169
00:09:08,110 --> 00:09:11,280
a small amount
of a powdery substance was found.

170
00:09:11,864 --> 00:09:14,784
<i>Detailed tests</i>
<i>are currently being carried out.</i>

171
00:09:15,701 --> 00:09:18,287
So in the end, we don't know anything.

172
00:09:18,371 --> 00:09:19,205
That's right.

173
00:09:20,081 --> 00:09:21,332
Not at this point.

174
00:09:21,415 --> 00:09:24,502
Contact me if you find out anything.

175
00:09:24,585 --> 00:09:25,503
Okay.

176
00:09:25,586 --> 00:09:27,380
Same to you, Ms. Dojima.

177
00:09:27,463 --> 00:09:31,050
I will if we find a witness who saw
a guy flying in the sky.

178
00:09:37,139 --> 00:09:38,349
It's ridiculous.

179
00:09:38,432 --> 00:09:39,934
First, we'll do questioning.

180
00:09:40,017 --> 00:09:40,851
Yes, ma'am!

181
00:09:40,935 --> 00:09:42,895
Could this powder-like stuff

182
00:09:43,646 --> 00:09:46,315
be wood dust from these trees?

183
00:09:46,399 --> 00:09:48,150
He climbed a tree and fell?

184
00:09:48,234 --> 00:09:50,778
Could be, if we found
alcohol intoxication.

185
00:09:50,861 --> 00:09:51,821
Then,

186
00:09:52,613 --> 00:09:54,407
from the roof of this stadium?

187
00:09:54,490 --> 00:09:57,451
But the distance from where he was found
is eight meters.

188
00:09:57,535 --> 00:09:59,578
If he fell from there…

189
00:10:01,497 --> 00:10:03,290
He would have to do a long jump.

190
00:10:04,250 --> 00:10:06,377
Did he even fall on his own?

191
00:10:06,460 --> 00:10:08,003
Maybe he was pushed?

192
00:10:08,087 --> 00:10:09,755
Someone with a grudge against him?

193
00:10:09,839 --> 00:10:11,340
That's not possible.

194
00:10:11,424 --> 00:10:12,341
What?

195
00:10:13,384 --> 00:10:17,012
There's no way someone
would hold a grudge against Hirono.

196
00:10:18,180 --> 00:10:19,515
Dr. Honda, let's go.

197
00:10:20,099 --> 00:10:23,853
Until the appraisal results are out,
I'm going to look into Hirono's work.

198
00:10:23,936 --> 00:10:25,020
At the hospital?

199
00:10:25,104 --> 00:10:28,733
Hirono cut the drinking session short,
saying he suddenly had work,

200
00:10:28,816 --> 00:10:30,109
and then died.

201
00:10:30,192 --> 00:10:32,862
He might have been meeting someone.

202
00:10:33,571 --> 00:10:35,030
Come on…

203
00:10:35,114 --> 00:10:37,575
When looking into
the victim's surroundings,

204
00:10:37,658 --> 00:10:41,036
it's convenient to have someone
who knew him well with me.

205
00:10:45,499 --> 00:10:48,085
I'd like to ask about
an incident at Miyagawa park…

206
00:10:48,169 --> 00:10:50,129
Thank you for your cooperation.

207
00:10:53,007 --> 00:10:53,924
Sir!

208
00:10:54,008 --> 00:10:56,427
Are you a resident of that apartment?

209
00:10:56,510 --> 00:10:57,386
Yes.

210
00:10:57,470 --> 00:10:59,597
Could I speak with you for a moment?

211
00:11:02,892 --> 00:11:04,226
A collision sound?

212
00:11:04,310 --> 00:11:05,936
There was a terrible noise.

213
00:11:06,645 --> 00:11:08,314
I rushed to open the window,

214
00:11:08,856 --> 00:11:10,524
but I couldn't see anything.

215
00:11:11,400 --> 00:11:13,777
Your daughter must have been startled too.

216
00:11:15,362 --> 00:11:16,322
Yes.

217
00:11:16,989 --> 00:11:19,992
I thought maybe
there had been an accident,

218
00:11:20,075 --> 00:11:23,078
but then I heard the sound
of a car driving away,

219
00:11:23,162 --> 00:11:24,830
so it was probably nothing.

220
00:11:26,123 --> 00:11:27,833
A car driving away…

221
00:11:29,543 --> 00:11:30,461
So good.

222
00:11:36,759 --> 00:11:39,220
We'll re-examine if there were
any suspicious vehicles.

223
00:11:39,303 --> 00:11:40,304
I'll re-examine.

224
00:11:40,387 --> 00:11:42,681
There's no way a human
would fall from the sky.

225
00:11:42,765 --> 00:11:43,933
No way at all.

226
00:11:44,725 --> 00:11:46,685
I've talked to the surgery department.

227
00:11:47,269 --> 00:11:48,521
Thank you.

228
00:11:48,604 --> 00:11:49,980
Just a moment.

229
00:11:50,064 --> 00:11:50,940
Okay.

230
00:11:54,944 --> 00:11:57,947
I really am glad
you came along, Dr. Honda.

231
00:11:59,907 --> 00:12:01,158
It's Hirono.

232
00:12:01,784 --> 00:12:03,536
I had to come.

233
00:12:06,956 --> 00:12:07,957
I…

234
00:12:09,416 --> 00:12:11,961
think I should just be doing autopsies.

235
00:12:12,044 --> 00:12:13,587
I am a forensic pathologist.

236
00:12:17,466 --> 00:12:20,261
What kind of person was Hirono?

237
00:12:21,136 --> 00:12:23,639
As a friend. It's just for reference.

238
00:12:25,975 --> 00:12:27,268
He was a good guy.

239
00:12:28,185 --> 00:12:29,270
Kind.

240
00:12:29,895 --> 00:12:31,063
Passionate.

241
00:12:33,607 --> 00:12:36,151
Not the kind of person
anyone would hold a grudge against.

242
00:12:36,986 --> 00:12:38,279
Definitely not.

243
00:12:41,699 --> 00:12:45,411
However, Hirono has passed away.

244
00:12:46,829 --> 00:12:52,918
Perhaps there were aspects of his life
that you didn't know about, Dr. Honda.

245
00:12:53,002 --> 00:12:54,378
Don't you think?

246
00:12:57,590 --> 00:12:59,174
Sorry to keep you waiting.

247
00:12:59,258 --> 00:13:00,384
Thank you.

248
00:13:11,020 --> 00:13:13,355
He was still so young, it's such a shame.

249
00:13:13,439 --> 00:13:16,400
What kind of person was Dr. Hirono?

250
00:13:16,483 --> 00:13:17,693
Who knows?

251
00:13:17,776 --> 00:13:19,945
We never talked about personal things.

252
00:13:20,029 --> 00:13:21,905
I only remember scolding him.

253
00:13:22,698 --> 00:13:23,574
What?

254
00:13:25,326 --> 00:13:28,621
You were his supervising doctor,
right, Dr. Imabayashi?

255
00:13:28,704 --> 00:13:32,625
Back when he was an intern.
He did nothing but make mistakes.

256
00:13:33,208 --> 00:13:36,295
I don't want to speak ill of him,
now that he's no more.

257
00:13:37,338 --> 00:13:40,341
Were things not going well at work?

258
00:13:41,425 --> 00:13:42,426
Yes.

259
00:13:43,052 --> 00:13:44,136
Or rather…

260
00:13:46,180 --> 00:13:47,056
What is it?

261
00:13:47,640 --> 00:13:48,807
Please tell us.

262
00:13:56,774 --> 00:13:58,150
Look at this.

263
00:13:58,233 --> 00:13:59,193
RESIGNATION LETTER

264
00:13:59,276 --> 00:14:01,070
I got the day before he died.

265
00:14:02,946 --> 00:14:05,240
He said he intended
to quit being a doctor.

266
00:14:06,158 --> 00:14:09,078
Well, I suppose he wasn't suited for it.

267
00:14:19,880 --> 00:14:21,173
Have you heard

268
00:14:21,799 --> 00:14:22,925
from Dr. Honda?

269
00:14:24,802 --> 00:14:25,636
No.

270
00:14:26,553 --> 00:14:27,554
Oh, okay.

271
00:14:37,314 --> 00:14:38,774
Do you know where you are?

272
00:14:39,233 --> 00:14:41,193
-Please.
-Bandages.

273
00:14:41,276 --> 00:14:43,112
I'll take this one.

274
00:14:43,195 --> 00:14:44,238
Thanks.

275
00:14:44,321 --> 00:14:45,781
I'll put some bandages on you.

276
00:14:45,864 --> 00:14:47,324
One, two, three, okay.

277
00:14:52,913 --> 00:14:53,998
Hey.

278
00:14:54,081 --> 00:14:56,792
-Ta-da.
-You little…

279
00:14:59,211 --> 00:15:00,713
-Here, cheers.
-Cheers.

280
00:15:02,923 --> 00:15:04,174
That hits the spot.

281
00:15:06,593 --> 00:15:08,512
You really are something.

282
00:15:08,595 --> 00:15:09,430
What?

283
00:15:09,513 --> 00:15:11,473
Your suturing is so fast.

284
00:15:12,516 --> 00:15:13,767
I guess.

285
00:15:15,185 --> 00:15:18,939
I think I'm better suited
for doing research after all.

286
00:15:23,652 --> 00:15:25,404
I want to be a good doctor.

287
00:15:27,573 --> 00:15:30,909
I listen to the voices of the living.

288
00:15:31,577 --> 00:15:34,955
You listen to the voices of the dead.

289
00:15:38,250 --> 00:15:40,002
Let's both do our best.

290
00:15:41,712 --> 00:15:42,671
Of course.

291
00:16:01,607 --> 00:16:03,317
-Excuse me.
-Yes?

292
00:16:03,400 --> 00:16:05,569
I'm Maki,
I'm getting my car repaired here.

293
00:16:05,652 --> 00:16:07,821
-Police.
-What?

294
00:16:08,655 --> 00:16:11,742
We're investigating an incident
that happened at Miyagawa Park.

295
00:16:11,825 --> 00:16:13,452
Can we talk to you?

296
00:16:14,036 --> 00:16:14,912
Why me?

297
00:16:14,995 --> 00:16:17,748
We're investigating cars that were
in the area that night

298
00:16:17,831 --> 00:16:19,875
and have been brought in for repairs.

299
00:16:19,958 --> 00:16:25,214
GPS records from your company car
show you parked there for 30 minutes.

300
00:16:25,297 --> 00:16:26,507
No, that was--

301
00:16:26,590 --> 00:16:31,470
Your bumper was badly dented, wasn't it?

302
00:16:32,554 --> 00:16:33,597
Let's see.

303
00:16:35,349 --> 00:16:37,226
What did you hit?

304
00:16:38,018 --> 00:16:39,311
I forgot.

305
00:16:40,229 --> 00:16:41,939
One more thing.

306
00:16:50,739 --> 00:16:53,075
So what did you hit?

307
00:16:55,327 --> 00:16:56,787
It turns out

308
00:16:56,870 --> 00:17:02,126
Hirono submitted his resignation
the day before the incident.

309
00:17:02,751 --> 00:17:08,966
It seems he was losing confidence because
his clinical work wasn't going well.

310
00:17:09,049 --> 00:17:11,426
He didn't tell you anything, Dr. Honda?

311
00:17:12,761 --> 00:17:15,889
Well, there are things you can't say
even to friends.

312
00:17:16,765 --> 00:17:17,891
That's right.

313
00:17:18,392 --> 00:17:20,978
He probably couldn't find
the timing to tell you.

314
00:17:21,061 --> 00:17:22,062
I understand that.

315
00:17:25,065 --> 00:17:26,441
Honda, you know--

316
00:17:26,525 --> 00:17:29,528
Don't start with the comforting words.

317
00:17:35,159 --> 00:17:38,620
Well then,
let's re-verify the cause of death.

318
00:17:38,704 --> 00:17:40,789
What does everyone think?

319
00:17:40,873 --> 00:17:44,585
If he was troubled by work,
maybe suicide is possible?

320
00:17:45,169 --> 00:17:47,254
It doesn't look like a suicide.

321
00:17:47,337 --> 00:17:48,297
Right.

322
00:17:51,925 --> 00:17:54,219
Dr. Honda, what do you think?

323
00:17:55,387 --> 00:17:56,430
Um…

324
00:17:59,266 --> 00:18:01,643
Listen, just as an example,

325
00:18:01,727 --> 00:18:06,815
is it possible he fell from a large truck
or a crane by accident?

326
00:18:06,899 --> 00:18:08,275
That might be possible.

327
00:18:08,358 --> 00:18:10,485
But considering the powder residue,

328
00:18:10,569 --> 00:18:13,322
falling from a tree
is also a possibility, I think.

329
00:18:13,405 --> 00:18:16,074
What could those abrasions be?

330
00:18:16,158 --> 00:18:19,786
Did he get caught in something
while he fell?

331
00:18:23,290 --> 00:18:25,959
Yoshimoto,
when will the test results be ready?

332
00:18:26,043 --> 00:18:28,253
They're at the forensic lab right now.

333
00:18:28,337 --> 00:18:29,880
I think they'll be out by noon.

334
00:18:29,963 --> 00:18:31,173
Understood.

335
00:18:31,757 --> 00:18:33,592
Accident, suicide, homicide.

336
00:18:33,675 --> 00:18:35,761
All possibilities remain.

337
00:18:35,844 --> 00:18:39,473
Dr. Honda,
let's go and re-examine the scene.

338
00:18:40,474 --> 00:18:41,683
Is it fun?

339
00:18:44,478 --> 00:18:46,063
Shamelessly digging up facts

340
00:18:46,647 --> 00:18:48,899
and talking about
someone's death like that?

341
00:18:52,611 --> 00:18:56,073
Look, that's not
what everyone's trying to do…

342
00:18:56,156 --> 00:19:00,202
Performing an autopsy, giving findings,
and diligently writing up tedious reports.

343
00:19:01,620 --> 00:19:04,581
That's about all we can do, isn't it?

344
00:19:08,126 --> 00:19:09,127
Let's go.

345
00:19:12,923 --> 00:19:15,175
I have an autopsy report to write.

346
00:19:15,259 --> 00:19:16,885
Take someone else.

347
00:19:18,929 --> 00:19:20,472
An animal jumped out suddenly.

348
00:19:20,555 --> 00:19:22,724
I thought, "Crap, I hit it!"
I panicked.

349
00:19:28,605 --> 00:19:30,023
At the time of the incident,

350
00:19:30,107 --> 00:19:32,401
you were parked there
for a long time. Why?

351
00:19:32,484 --> 00:19:34,820
That was to wipe the blood off the car.

352
00:19:34,903 --> 00:19:36,613
I can't handle blood.

353
00:19:36,697 --> 00:19:39,658
I got a bit lightheaded,
so I was resting with the window open.

354
00:19:41,118 --> 00:19:42,286
Ms. Dojima.

355
00:19:43,537 --> 00:19:45,122
The traffic police informed us

356
00:19:45,205 --> 00:19:49,042
that no brake marks that would indicate
an accident occurred have been found.

357
00:19:55,757 --> 00:19:56,758
Pop!

358
00:19:58,969 --> 00:20:00,262
What are you doing?

359
00:20:00,345 --> 00:20:01,221
Oh, hey.

360
00:20:01,305 --> 00:20:03,974
I tried to contact you
but couldn't get through.

361
00:20:04,057 --> 00:20:05,851
Sorry, I've been busy.

362
00:20:05,934 --> 00:20:10,564
A doctor says a body fell from the sky,
and the crime scene is in total chaos.

363
00:20:11,732 --> 00:20:13,817
Please don't inform my company.

364
00:20:13,900 --> 00:20:14,901
Yeah, all right.

365
00:20:14,985 --> 00:20:16,903
Is he a person of interest?

366
00:20:16,987 --> 00:20:18,739
He hit an animal near the scene.

367
00:20:18,822 --> 00:20:21,825
Did you hear any sounds
like a collision near the scene?

368
00:20:21,908 --> 00:20:22,951
What?

369
00:20:23,035 --> 00:20:24,911
No, nothing in particular.

370
00:20:24,995 --> 00:20:27,164
The interrogation is over.

371
00:20:30,292 --> 00:20:31,793
Hey! What about the sound?

372
00:20:31,877 --> 00:20:32,753
What?

373
00:20:32,836 --> 00:20:34,880
You didn't hear a sound,

374
00:20:34,963 --> 00:20:36,465
but was there anything else?

375
00:20:36,548 --> 00:20:38,508
No, well…

376
00:20:39,134 --> 00:20:40,635
There was kind of a smell.

377
00:20:40,719 --> 00:20:42,012
What kind of smell?

378
00:20:42,095 --> 00:20:43,055
It was like

379
00:20:43,972 --> 00:20:45,098
something rotten.

380
00:21:00,989 --> 00:21:02,407
Why don't you take a break?

381
00:21:04,201 --> 00:21:05,869
Don't bother with that.

382
00:21:07,829 --> 00:21:10,165
Caring for my colleagues
is part of the job.

383
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:14,086
A very bureaucratic way of thinking.

384
00:21:15,045 --> 00:21:16,338
But I'm fine.

385
00:21:24,679 --> 00:21:25,555
Take this.

386
00:21:28,016 --> 00:21:31,019
They say you need sugar
to make your brain work.

387
00:21:33,688 --> 00:21:35,357
You're quite the meddler.

388
00:21:38,944 --> 00:21:40,112
I suppose so.

389
00:21:41,571 --> 00:21:42,781
Oh, I get it.

390
00:21:43,824 --> 00:21:46,868
It would be a stain on
a bureaucrat's career if someone quit.

391
00:21:48,328 --> 00:21:49,204
Quit?

392
00:21:49,871 --> 00:21:52,165
I can't do this job anymore.

393
00:21:54,292 --> 00:21:56,002
This case made it clear to me.

394
00:21:57,295 --> 00:21:58,296
I just…

395
00:22:00,882 --> 00:22:03,051
can't handle this job.

396
00:22:16,982 --> 00:22:18,024
I also…

397
00:22:20,610 --> 00:22:23,071
did not intend to do this kind of work.

398
00:22:26,408 --> 00:22:28,410
And I'm always hating

399
00:22:29,536 --> 00:22:31,121
how useless I am.

400
00:22:34,416 --> 00:22:36,418
But maybe everyone feels that way.

401
00:22:39,629 --> 00:22:41,047
I wonder how

402
00:22:42,549 --> 00:22:44,217
Hirono felt.

403
00:22:57,189 --> 00:22:58,815
I never thought…

404
00:23:04,321 --> 00:23:06,823
I would never be able to see him again.

405
00:23:10,827 --> 00:23:12,329
If I had known

406
00:23:13,663 --> 00:23:15,123
it would be the last time…

407
00:23:17,542 --> 00:23:19,836
I would have said so many things.

408
00:23:35,602 --> 00:23:37,229
It's not over yet.

409
00:23:40,482 --> 00:23:42,150
You're a forensic pathologist.

410
00:23:58,833 --> 00:24:00,293
Hello, this is Masumi.

411
00:24:00,377 --> 00:24:03,463
This is Yoshimoto.
The results of the lab test are in.

412
00:24:03,546 --> 00:24:04,839
All right.

413
00:24:04,923 --> 00:24:06,299
I'll head back now--

414
00:24:12,097 --> 00:24:13,181
<i>Doctor?</i>

415
00:24:13,723 --> 00:24:15,141
<i>Are you there?</i>

416
00:24:15,225 --> 00:24:16,601
I'll call you back.

417
00:24:28,280 --> 00:24:31,449
No components
matching the powder found on the body

418
00:24:31,533 --> 00:24:35,620
were detected from the trees
or the stadium roof.

419
00:24:36,705 --> 00:24:37,914
Then, Hirono…

420
00:24:38,498 --> 00:24:42,711
It seems like he at least
didn't throw himself from anywhere.

421
00:24:45,630 --> 00:24:49,509
I'm going back to check the test results.

422
00:24:49,592 --> 00:24:54,097
However, a piece to solve the cause of
Hirono's death is still missing.

423
00:24:56,725 --> 00:24:58,101
I never found out

424
00:24:58,768 --> 00:25:00,270
what he was going to tell me.

425
00:25:02,397 --> 00:25:03,481
I'll find it.

426
00:25:07,902 --> 00:25:09,237
All right…

427
00:25:11,364 --> 00:25:13,616
Sorry, did Hirono tell you anything?

428
00:25:13,700 --> 00:25:15,201
Excuse me, I'm busy right now.

429
00:25:15,285 --> 00:25:16,411
Anything will help.

430
00:25:16,494 --> 00:25:18,371
No, I didn't know him well, sorry.

431
00:25:19,164 --> 00:25:20,999
Did anything seem different?

432
00:25:21,082 --> 00:25:22,917
Sorry, I really have no idea.

433
00:25:23,001 --> 00:25:24,711
Excuse me, may I ask you?

434
00:25:26,796 --> 00:25:28,089
Finally, I'm done!

435
00:25:28,173 --> 00:25:29,632
Me too!

436
00:25:29,716 --> 00:25:30,717
Finally.

437
00:25:35,847 --> 00:25:36,973
Shall we all do it?

438
00:25:37,057 --> 00:25:39,601
-Dr. Honda's work.
-Yes.

439
00:25:39,684 --> 00:25:41,644
I guess we have to.

440
00:25:41,728 --> 00:25:42,645
Okay, thank you.

441
00:25:42,729 --> 00:25:43,521
Sure.

442
00:25:43,605 --> 00:25:45,398
Can anyone talk to me?

443
00:25:45,482 --> 00:25:47,067
I didn't know him well, sorry.

444
00:25:47,150 --> 00:25:48,401
I've got work to do.

445
00:25:48,485 --> 00:25:49,486
But…

446
00:25:50,195 --> 00:25:52,447
-Please!
-I'm sorry.

447
00:25:53,740 --> 00:25:55,533
Are you talking about Dr. Hirono?

448
00:25:56,826 --> 00:25:59,287
Where did Dr. Hirono go?

449
00:25:59,371 --> 00:26:01,790
He hasn't fixed my tummy yet.

450
00:26:02,665 --> 00:26:03,500
Well…

451
00:26:04,209 --> 00:26:07,921
Dr. Hirono has gone somewhere far away.

452
00:26:08,797 --> 00:26:11,174
But he gave me a message for you.

453
00:26:11,257 --> 00:26:12,425
A message?

454
00:26:12,509 --> 00:26:13,510
Yes.

455
00:26:14,511 --> 00:26:18,598
He said he's made all the preparations
to fix your tummy perfectly,

456
00:26:19,349 --> 00:26:21,851
so you can just relax
and focus on getting better.

457
00:26:21,935 --> 00:26:22,936
Really?

458
00:26:23,812 --> 00:26:24,604
Yes.

459
00:26:25,230 --> 00:26:26,189
So,

460
00:26:26,981 --> 00:26:27,899
do your best.

461
00:26:30,402 --> 00:26:32,612
Did Dr. Hirono go away

462
00:26:33,905 --> 00:26:35,698
because he made people angry?

463
00:26:38,243 --> 00:26:41,162
A scary man was really angry with him.

464
00:26:43,039 --> 00:26:45,500
He said, "It's your fault she died."

465
00:26:53,967 --> 00:26:55,802
The detailed results are out.

466
00:26:55,885 --> 00:26:58,221
The powder detected on the body

467
00:26:58,304 --> 00:27:01,307
was sodium bicarbonate
containing hydrogen sulfide.

468
00:27:01,391 --> 00:27:05,520
There was also a testimony
about a strange smell at the scene.

469
00:27:06,020 --> 00:27:08,815
It must be putrefactive gas
generated by this.

470
00:27:08,898 --> 00:27:12,652
Could this be why the body
expanded after death?

471
00:27:12,735 --> 00:27:14,779
<i>The gas escaped,</i>

472
00:27:14,863 --> 00:27:16,990
<i>making the body move</i>
<i>as if it were convulsing.</i>

473
00:27:17,073 --> 00:27:18,366
What?

474
00:27:18,450 --> 00:27:20,660
Corpses can move?

475
00:27:20,743 --> 00:27:22,954
It's a special case of post-mortem change.

476
00:27:23,037 --> 00:27:26,541
It's when the body temporarily moves
due to putrefactive gases or rigor mortis.

477
00:27:26,624 --> 00:27:29,544
This also explains
the surrounding blood spatters.

478
00:27:29,627 --> 00:27:33,548
They must have gotten scattered
when he had a violent convulsion.

479
00:27:33,631 --> 00:27:35,550
What happened?

480
00:27:35,633 --> 00:27:38,845
There may still be a piece
we haven't found yet.

481
00:27:44,601 --> 00:27:46,853
Hello, this is Medical Examiner Japan.

482
00:27:48,229 --> 00:27:49,314
It's Dr. Honda.

483
00:27:49,397 --> 00:27:50,440
Got it.

484
00:27:53,651 --> 00:27:54,736
This is Masumi.

485
00:27:55,320 --> 00:27:57,113
I've found a clue.

486
00:27:57,197 --> 00:27:58,615
I think I might know

487
00:27:58,698 --> 00:28:01,910
what job Hirono was talking about
on the night of the incident.

488
00:28:02,994 --> 00:28:03,953
It was…

489
00:28:08,374 --> 00:28:10,793
What did he say?

490
00:28:58,258 --> 00:28:59,509
Dr. Masumi?

491
00:28:59,592 --> 00:29:01,803
The pieces may just

492
00:29:03,137 --> 00:29:04,639
be coming together.

493
00:29:24,534 --> 00:29:27,871
I would like to talk to you
about the incident that occurred

494
00:29:27,954 --> 00:29:29,247
at Miyagawa Park.

495
00:29:32,625 --> 00:29:34,085
Take a seat.

496
00:29:44,345 --> 00:29:45,638
Mr. Takemura.

497
00:29:47,640 --> 00:29:49,517
On the night of the incident,

498
00:29:49,601 --> 00:29:51,352
<i>you testified that you heard</i>

499
00:29:51,436 --> 00:29:54,772
<i>a collision sound</i>
<i>and the sound of a car driving away.</i>

500
00:29:54,856 --> 00:29:55,899
Since then,

501
00:29:56,733 --> 00:29:59,485
no other information has come up.

502
00:30:00,320 --> 00:30:02,196
Not one other person

503
00:30:02,906 --> 00:30:04,866
heard such sounds.

504
00:30:07,118 --> 00:30:08,161
So what?

505
00:30:13,958 --> 00:30:16,127
There were findings on Hirono's body

506
00:30:16,210 --> 00:30:19,589
that looked as though
he had fallen from the sky.

507
00:30:20,840 --> 00:30:21,799
However…

508
00:30:24,427 --> 00:30:28,222
that actually was not the case.

509
00:30:31,059 --> 00:30:33,144
The key to solving the mystery

510
00:30:33,770 --> 00:30:36,022
was the scars on the body.

511
00:30:36,773 --> 00:30:40,360
<i>There were burn-like abrasions</i>
<i>on the right arm and left leg of the body.</i>

512
00:30:41,361 --> 00:30:45,198
There is one hypothesis
that makes these traces possible.

513
00:30:46,866 --> 00:30:50,828
When a person falls in a narrow space
where movement is restricted,

514
00:30:50,912 --> 00:30:56,334
their limbs will rub against the walls
as they fall.

515
00:30:56,417 --> 00:30:57,543
In this case,

516
00:30:58,127 --> 00:31:00,088
<i>near where the victim was found,</i>

517
00:31:00,797 --> 00:31:02,006
<i>in a manhole.</i>

518
00:31:04,342 --> 00:31:09,430
In other words,
the victim did not fall from the sky.

519
00:31:10,390 --> 00:31:13,142
<i>He fell from the ground into the deep,</i>

520
00:31:14,227 --> 00:31:16,229
<i>and died there.</i>

521
00:31:19,232 --> 00:31:22,568
It's natural that no one heard a sound.

522
00:31:23,945 --> 00:31:26,864
The collision sound
echoed inside the manhole,

523
00:31:26,948 --> 00:31:29,492
and no one could hear it.

524
00:31:30,535 --> 00:31:33,913
In his body we detected both
hydrogen sulfide

525
00:31:33,997 --> 00:31:37,875
and sodium bicarbonate,
which is used to neutralize it.

526
00:31:37,959 --> 00:31:43,381
These matched what could be found
inside this sewer.

527
00:31:45,216 --> 00:31:48,636
You're a sewer worker,
aren't you, Mr. Takemura?

528
00:31:48,720 --> 00:31:51,931
<i>We've obtained a warrant earlier</i>

529
00:31:52,015 --> 00:31:57,687
and seized your work equipment from
the vehicle parked near your home.

530
00:31:57,770 --> 00:32:01,274
It's only a matter of time
before we have clear physical evidence.

531
00:32:06,279 --> 00:32:07,572
The person who died

532
00:32:08,531 --> 00:32:10,825
was a surgeon
at Meiwa University Hospital,

533
00:32:11,784 --> 00:32:13,077
Tomoki Hirono.

534
00:32:14,996 --> 00:32:16,539
You know him, don't you?

535
00:32:20,543 --> 00:32:21,961
Six months ago,

536
00:32:23,463 --> 00:32:25,715
your only family member,

537
00:32:25,798 --> 00:32:31,137
your daughter Yumi was transported
to the ER at Meiwa University Hospital.

538
00:32:31,763 --> 00:32:33,139
Yumi! Stay with me!

539
00:32:33,222 --> 00:32:34,932
Don't worry, we'll help you.

540
00:32:35,016 --> 00:32:36,684
Temperature 37.2, blood pressure--

541
00:32:36,768 --> 00:32:38,519
<i>The one who first examined her</i>

542
00:32:38,603 --> 00:32:41,105
<i>was Hirono,</i>
<i>who was still an intern at the time.</i>

543
00:32:42,106 --> 00:32:44,525
The blood tests
show no particular problems.

544
00:32:45,318 --> 00:32:47,361
She may have mild appendicitis,

545
00:32:47,445 --> 00:32:49,906
so we'll have her stay
at the hospital for observation.

546
00:32:51,115 --> 00:32:52,408
Thank you.

547
00:32:56,329 --> 00:32:58,039
<i>But three days later,</i>

548
00:32:58,664 --> 00:33:00,750
<i>Yumi's condition suddenly worsened,</i>

549
00:33:00,833 --> 00:33:02,960
<i>and sadly, she passed away.</i>

550
00:33:04,962 --> 00:33:05,963
Murderer.

551
00:33:06,047 --> 00:33:07,298
You killed her!

552
00:33:07,882 --> 00:33:09,967
Give me… Give me Yumi back!

553
00:33:10,051 --> 00:33:13,471
<i>-You directed your anger at Hirono.</i>
-Hey! Say something!

554
00:33:13,554 --> 00:33:15,098
<i>For a mistake in his diagnosis.</i>

555
00:33:15,681 --> 00:33:17,266
You killed her!

556
00:33:17,350 --> 00:33:19,602
I'm telling you to bring out that intern!

557
00:33:19,685 --> 00:33:20,770
Hurry up!

558
00:33:20,853 --> 00:33:23,231
-What are you doing? Stop.
-Hey!

559
00:33:23,773 --> 00:33:25,983
<i>You went to the hospital</i>
<i>many times after that.</i>

560
00:33:26,067 --> 00:33:27,819
<i>That's medical malpractice, right?</i>

561
00:33:27,902 --> 00:33:30,863
<i>Continuing to claim</i>
<i>there had been a misdiagnosis.</i>

562
00:33:31,948 --> 00:33:32,990
But…

563
00:33:35,535 --> 00:33:38,454
the hospital forbade Hirono
from handling it.

564
00:33:40,581 --> 00:33:42,583
He lost his daughter!

565
00:33:42,667 --> 00:33:44,836
We should apologize with sincerity.

566
00:33:44,919 --> 00:33:48,339
If we apologize publicly,
it means we're admitting a mistake.

567
00:33:50,007 --> 00:33:51,759
I should have urged more strongly

568
00:33:51,843 --> 00:33:55,805
for a retest of the coagulation function
of her blood after the first test.

569
00:33:56,430 --> 00:33:58,015
But isn't the biggest issue

570
00:33:58,099 --> 00:34:01,185
the mistake made in the hemostatic
procedure during surgery?

571
00:34:03,271 --> 00:34:05,439
You won't be able
to become a surgeon either.

572
00:34:09,861 --> 00:34:12,697
You were the one
who performed the initial treatment.

573
00:34:13,447 --> 00:34:15,908
Go ahead, if you want to
give up your future as a doctor.

574
00:34:22,290 --> 00:34:23,207
<i>But</i>

575
00:34:23,749 --> 00:34:25,293
<i>Hirono didn't run away.</i>

576
00:34:33,843 --> 00:34:34,886
<i>He was…</i>

577
00:34:35,761 --> 00:34:37,638
He was trying to expose the hospital

578
00:34:37,722 --> 00:34:42,351
for covering up the medical malpractice
they had committed.

579
00:34:44,395 --> 00:34:46,564
A statement written by Hirono

580
00:34:46,647 --> 00:34:51,110
that explained all of this
was also found in your room.

581
00:34:51,194 --> 00:34:54,238
Does that not mean you knew all of this?

582
00:34:56,741 --> 00:34:57,700
So…

583
00:34:59,327 --> 00:35:00,661
why did you do it?

584
00:35:03,331 --> 00:35:04,957
Why do that to Hirono?

585
00:35:07,877 --> 00:35:09,086
No.

586
00:35:11,464 --> 00:35:12,632
That's not it.

587
00:35:25,394 --> 00:35:27,521
<i>This is Hirono</i>
<i>from Meiwa University Hospital.</i>

588
00:35:28,147 --> 00:35:30,566
<i>Could I talk to you directly?</i>

589
00:35:38,616 --> 00:35:40,785
<i>So now he decides to contact me?</i>

590
00:35:40,868 --> 00:35:44,789
<i>I thought he'd want to settle this</i>
<i>with money, and wanted to refuse.</i>

591
00:35:44,872 --> 00:35:46,707
After the examination is over…

592
00:35:46,791 --> 00:35:48,292
But then…

593
00:35:48,376 --> 00:35:49,669
Let's go for a walk?

594
00:35:49,752 --> 00:35:50,920
-Yes!
-Yes!

595
00:35:51,003 --> 00:35:52,129
Yay!

596
00:35:52,213 --> 00:35:53,256
Nice.

597
00:35:53,339 --> 00:35:55,675
<i>He's the one who killed Yumi,</i>

598
00:35:56,259 --> 00:35:59,720
<i>and yet he's pretending</i>
<i>to be a good doctor, acting so happy!</i>

599
00:35:59,804 --> 00:36:02,056
-Can I have this?
-Sure.

600
00:36:02,139 --> 00:36:03,432
Really? Thanks.

601
00:36:03,516 --> 00:36:05,101
<i>That's why that night…</i>

602
00:36:10,898 --> 00:36:13,276
COME TO MIYAGAWA PARK AT 11:00 P.M.

603
00:36:13,359 --> 00:36:15,194
Sorry, it's work.

604
00:36:35,256 --> 00:36:36,424
Mr. Takemura,

605
00:36:37,049 --> 00:36:38,759
thank you for your time.

606
00:36:40,594 --> 00:36:41,804
No matter how much

607
00:36:43,055 --> 00:36:45,391
I apologize for Yumi,
I can never make amends.

608
00:36:46,183 --> 00:36:49,228
But that's why
I want to take responsibility--

609
00:36:49,312 --> 00:36:50,980
Don't give me that crap.

610
00:36:57,278 --> 00:36:58,946
You killed her.

611
00:37:00,781 --> 00:37:01,907
You…

612
00:37:02,616 --> 00:37:03,743
killed Yumi…

613
00:37:09,623 --> 00:37:11,167
-You're the one…
-I…

614
00:37:11,250 --> 00:37:12,585
As a doctor, I tried to--

615
00:37:12,668 --> 00:37:15,171
-You killed her!
-Please, listen to me!

616
00:37:15,254 --> 00:37:17,590
You killed her!

617
00:37:53,667 --> 00:37:54,960
REPORT OF INTERNAL MISCONDUCT

618
00:37:55,044 --> 00:37:56,545
1. THE FIRST EXAMINATION

619
00:37:56,629 --> 00:37:58,839
TOMOKI HIRONO

620
00:37:59,757 --> 00:38:01,926
<i>By the time I found his report,</i>

621
00:38:02,718 --> 00:38:04,095
<i>it was too late.</i>

622
00:38:29,453 --> 00:38:30,955
Hey. Hey!

623
00:38:47,972 --> 00:38:49,765
But I'm not in the wrong.

624
00:38:50,891 --> 00:38:53,894
His report is proof.
It was all their fault!

625
00:38:53,978 --> 00:38:55,563
Don't give me that!

626
00:38:57,189 --> 00:39:00,568
Hirono was planning to
expose the medical malpractice

627
00:39:01,318 --> 00:39:03,154
and quit being a doctor!

628
00:39:05,406 --> 00:39:07,408
He was taking responsibility.

629
00:39:07,491 --> 00:39:08,534
Dr. Honda.

630
00:39:13,706 --> 00:39:14,915
He…

631
00:39:17,376 --> 00:39:19,712
He was an incredible doctor.

632
00:39:19,795 --> 00:39:21,213
More than anyone.

633
00:39:24,508 --> 00:39:25,634
Why…

634
00:39:27,678 --> 00:39:29,972
Why did he have to have
such a horrible end?

635
00:39:41,984 --> 00:39:46,572
You could say that it was Hirono
who gave us the final clues

636
00:39:47,573 --> 00:39:48,699
to solve the case.

637
00:39:54,747 --> 00:39:57,166
<i>He wiped away</i>
<i>the bloodstains from the murder,</i>

638
00:39:57,249 --> 00:39:59,502
<i>disposed of Hirono's smartphone,</i>

639
00:40:00,085 --> 00:40:03,214
<i>and then it should have been over,</i>
<i>once he hid the body.</i>

640
00:40:06,717 --> 00:40:09,553
<i>But why couldn't he do that?</i>

641
00:40:35,538 --> 00:40:37,248
Post-mortem change.

642
00:40:39,458 --> 00:40:42,545
He glared at me
as if he had come back to life.

643
00:40:46,090 --> 00:40:47,424
And so,

644
00:40:48,634 --> 00:40:50,010
I left him there.

645
00:40:56,725 --> 00:40:58,227
It was for Yumi.

646
00:41:01,855 --> 00:41:03,816
It was all for Yumi.

647
00:41:33,846 --> 00:41:35,848
It's miraculous.

648
00:41:38,100 --> 00:41:41,645
If he had disposed of the body…

649
00:41:45,357 --> 00:41:47,401
the truth might never

650
00:41:49,820 --> 00:41:51,488
have come out.

651
00:41:58,871 --> 00:41:59,830
He…

652
00:42:01,332 --> 00:42:02,791
To the very end…

653
00:42:06,837 --> 00:42:09,381
he was such an amazing guy.

654
00:42:23,354 --> 00:42:26,565
I heard that the medical malpractice
is going to be made public.

655
00:42:26,649 --> 00:42:27,483
Yeah.

656
00:42:27,566 --> 00:42:30,694
Apparently, Ms. Kiryu negotiated for it
at the Ministry.

657
00:42:30,778 --> 00:42:32,780
Wow, I see.

658
00:42:32,863 --> 00:42:34,573
Not bad, for a bureaucrat.

659
00:42:35,532 --> 00:42:36,575
Here.

660
00:42:38,744 --> 00:42:39,828
What?

661
00:42:39,912 --> 00:42:41,205
You did them for us?

662
00:42:41,288 --> 00:42:43,874
No, I was just paying back the favor
from the other day.

663
00:42:43,957 --> 00:42:45,876
You could just say thank you.

664
00:42:45,959 --> 00:42:47,002
Well, it's fine.

665
00:42:47,086 --> 00:42:48,003
Thank you.

666
00:42:48,087 --> 00:42:49,046
Thank you.

667
00:42:49,129 --> 00:42:49,963
Thanks.

668
00:42:50,047 --> 00:42:51,090
Well,

669
00:42:51,715 --> 00:42:52,800
see you.

670
00:42:52,883 --> 00:42:54,468
-Take care.
-Bye.

671
00:42:57,471 --> 00:42:59,014
Oh, good morning.

672
00:42:59,098 --> 00:43:00,432
Good morning.

673
00:43:01,016 --> 00:43:02,142
Good morning.

674
00:43:06,647 --> 00:43:07,690
Um…

675
00:43:12,444 --> 00:43:13,821
Thank you.

676
00:43:49,940 --> 00:43:51,275
I've come to listen

677
00:43:51,900 --> 00:43:53,527
to what you have to say.

678
00:43:56,321 --> 00:43:57,948
I'm a bit late, though.

679
00:44:06,373 --> 00:44:08,041
TNS NEWS ONLINE

680
00:44:08,125 --> 00:44:09,668
4TH CASE OF WOMAN FOUND STRANGLED

681
00:44:15,758 --> 00:44:18,177
SHIRAMINE SERIAL FEMICIDE CASE
RESEARCH DATA

682
